1
00:00:19,753 --> 00:00:22,221
[ Clattering Sound ]

2
00:00:23,690 --> 00:00:25,920
[ Man ]
I'm talkin'about friendship.

3
00:00:26,026 --> 00:00:28,688
I'm talkin'about character.

4
00:00:28,762 --> 00:00:33,199
I'm talkin'about- -
Hell, Leo, I ain't embarrassed
to use the word.

5
00:00:33,266 --> 00:00:36,429
I'm talkin' about ethics.

6
00:00:36,503 --> 00:00:38,562
You know I'm a sportin' man.

7
00:00:38,638 --> 00:00:41,072
I like to lay the occasional bet.
[ Chuckles ]

8
00:00:41,141 --> 00:00:43,701
But I ain't that sportin'.

9
00:00:43,810 --> 00:00:46,711
When I fix a fight--
Say I pay a three to one favorite...

10
00:00:46,780 --> 00:00:48,805
to throw a goddamned fight.

11
00:00:48,882 --> 00:00:53,012
I figure I got the right
to expect that fight
to go off at three to one.

12
00:00:53,086 --> 00:00:56,817
But every time I lay in bed
with this son of a bitch
Bernie Bernbaum,

13
00:00:56,890 --> 00:01:00,189
before I know it,
the odds is even up.

14
00:01:00,260 --> 00:01:02,751
Or worse, I'm bettin'
on the short money.

15
00:01:02,862 --> 00:01:05,126
The sheeny knows
I like sure things.

16
00:01:05,198 --> 00:01:08,656
He's sellin' the information
I fixed the fight.

17
00:01:08,735 --> 00:01:11,101
Out of town money
comes pouring in.

18
00:01:11,171 --> 00:01:13,401
The odds go straight to hell.

19
00:01:13,473 --> 00:01:16,840
I don't know who
he's sellin' to-- maybe
the Los Angeles combine.

20
00:01:16,910 --> 00:01:18,844
I don't know. The point is,

21
00:01:18,912 --> 00:01:23,076
Bernie ain't satisfied
with the honest dollar
he can make off the vig.

22
00:01:23,183 --> 00:01:26,414
He ain't satisfied with
the business I do on his book.

23
00:01:26,486 --> 00:01:29,387
He is sellin' tips on how I bet.

24
00:01:29,456 --> 00:01:32,619
And that means part
of the payoff that should
be riding on my hip...

25
00:01:32,692 --> 00:01:34,853
is riding on someone else's.

26
00:01:34,928 --> 00:01:37,453
So, back we go
to these questions--

27
00:01:37,530 --> 00:01:41,432
friendship, character,

28
00:01:41,501 --> 00:01:43,833
ethics.

29
00:01:46,973 --> 00:01:49,032
So, it's clear what I'm saying?

30
00:01:50,477 --> 00:01:53,344
As mud.

31
00:01:55,915 --> 00:02:01,615
It's gettin' so a businessman
can't expect no return
from a fixed fight.

32
00:02:01,688 --> 00:02:05,146
Now, if you can't trust a fix,
what can you trust?

33
00:02:05,225 --> 00:02:08,626
For a good return, you gotta
go bettin'on chance,

34
00:02:08,695 --> 00:02:10,925
and then you're
back with anarchy.

35
00:02:10,997 --> 00:02:12,931
Right back in the jungle.

36
00:02:12,999 --> 00:02:18,062
That's why ethics is important- -
what separates us
from the animals,

37
00:02:18,171 --> 00:02:20,639
the beasts of burden,
the beasts of prey.

38
00:02:20,707 --> 00:02:22,675
Ethics.

39
00:02:22,742 --> 00:02:26,940
Whereas, uh, Bernie Bernbaum
is a horse of a different color,

40
00:02:27,013 --> 00:02:30,744
ethics-wise, as in
he ain't got any.

41
00:02:30,817 --> 00:02:34,913
- You sure it's Bernie
selling you out?
- It ain't elves.

42
00:02:34,988 --> 00:02:38,890
- No one else knows about the fix?
- No one that ain't got ethics.

43
00:02:38,958 --> 00:02:41,984
What about the fighters
you pay to tank out?

44
00:02:42,061 --> 00:02:45,997
We only pick fighters
we know we can put
the fear of God in.

45
00:02:46,065 --> 00:02:48,363
Any other bookies know?
You play anyone else's book?

46
00:02:48,434 --> 00:02:51,665
I-I lay an occasional bet
with Mink Larouie.

47
00:02:51,738 --> 00:02:54,263
- But it ain't Mink.
I'll vouch for that.
- How do you know?

48
00:02:54,340 --> 00:02:57,605
It ain't Mink.
Mink is Eddie Dane's boy.

49
00:02:57,710 --> 00:03:01,476
Of course the Dane
always knows about the fix.

50
00:03:01,548 --> 00:03:03,675
And what the hell
is that supposed to mean?

51
00:03:03,750 --> 00:03:07,277
Let it drift. All it means is
a lot of people know.

52
00:03:07,353 --> 00:03:09,719
I guess you ain't
been listenin'.

53
00:03:09,789 --> 00:03:11,984
Sure, other people know.
[ Chuckles ]

54
00:03:12,058 --> 00:03:14,754
That's why we gotta go
to this question of character...

55
00:03:14,861 --> 00:03:18,558
to determine just who, exactly,
is chiselin' in on my fix.

56
00:03:18,631 --> 00:03:22,397
And that's how we know
that it's Bernie Bernbaum,
the shmatte kid--

57
00:03:22,468 --> 00:03:25,562
'cause ethically,
he's kinda shaky.

58
00:03:26,806 --> 00:03:30,867
- So you want to kill him.
- For starters.

59
00:03:45,325 --> 00:03:49,853
Sorry, Caspar.
Bernie pays for protection.

60
00:03:51,364 --> 00:03:54,561
Listen, Leo, I ain't
askin' you for permission.

61
00:03:54,667 --> 00:03:58,831
I'm tellin' you as a courtesy.
I need to do this thing,
so it's gonna get done.

62
00:03:58,905 --> 00:04:00,839
And I'm tellin' you, as
a courtesy, you'll have trouble.

63
00:04:00,907 --> 00:04:04,707
You came here to see if
I'd kick if you killed Bernie.
Well, there's your answer.

64
00:04:04,777 --> 00:04:08,440
I pay off to you every month
like a greengrocer

65
00:04:08,514 --> 00:04:10,505
a lot more than the shmatte,

66
00:04:10,583 --> 00:04:12,551
and I'm sick of gettin'
the high hat.

67
00:04:12,619 --> 00:04:15,611
You pay off for protection
just like everyone else.

68
00:04:15,722 --> 00:04:18,520
As far as I know, and
what I don't know in this town
ain't worth knowing,

69
00:04:18,591 --> 00:04:20,582
the cops haven't closed
any of your dives...

70
00:04:20,660 --> 00:04:23,151
and the D.A. Hasn't touched
any of your rackets.

71
00:04:23,229 --> 00:04:25,754
You haven't bought any license
to kill bookies,

72
00:04:25,832 --> 00:04:27,823
and today I ain't sellin'any.

73
00:04:27,900 --> 00:04:30,801
So take your flunky and dangle.

74
00:04:30,903 --> 00:04:35,306
You think I'm some guinea
fresh off the boat,
and you can kick me.

75
00:04:35,375 --> 00:04:39,436
But I'm too big for that now.
I'm sick of takin'
the strap from you, Leo.

76
00:04:39,512 --> 00:04:41,878
I'm sick of marching
into this goddamn office...

77
00:04:41,948 --> 00:04:43,973
to kiss your Irish ass,

78
00:04:44,050 --> 00:04:46,541
and I'm sick of the high hat!

79
00:05:03,136 --> 00:05:06,435
You's fancy pants, all of youse.

80
00:05:08,341 --> 00:05:10,809
Johnny?

81
00:05:10,877 --> 00:05:14,210
You're exactly as big
as I let you be and no bigger,

82
00:05:14,280 --> 00:05:16,578
and don't forget it, ever.

83
00:05:19,152 --> 00:05:21,086
That's right, Leo.

84
00:05:21,154 --> 00:05:23,247
You're the big shot
around here,

85
00:05:23,323 --> 00:05:26,986
and I'm just some schnook
likes to get slapped around.

86
00:05:32,198 --> 00:05:34,325
[ Chuckles ]

87
00:05:34,400 --> 00:05:37,369
Twist a pig's ear,
watch him squeal.

88
00:05:46,079 --> 00:05:49,606
- Bad play, Leo.
- Who got up the wrong side, huh?

89
00:05:49,716 --> 00:05:52,549
- Same side as always.
- That's what I mean.
Still owe money to--

90
00:05:52,618 --> 00:05:56,076
Who is your bookie, Lazarre?
I could put it right for you.

91
00:05:56,155 --> 00:05:59,181
- Thanks, Leo. I don't need it.
- In a pig's eye.

92
00:05:59,258 --> 00:06:01,123
You haven't played
a winner in six weeks.

93
00:06:01,194 --> 00:06:03,594
People will speak ill of me
if I let him break your legs.

94
00:06:03,663 --> 00:06:07,565
- People will say I had it coming.
- And they'll be right,
but that ain't the point.

95
00:06:07,633 --> 00:06:11,501
Call me a bighearted slob,
but I'm gonna square it
for you, yeah.

96
00:06:11,571 --> 00:06:15,029
I think I'll do that
this very same night.

97
00:06:15,108 --> 00:06:18,976
Lookin' at you mopin' around
takes away all my--

98
00:06:19,045 --> 00:06:21,639
What do you call it?
"Joy de veever"?

99
00:06:21,714 --> 00:06:24,808
- Joie de vivre.
- Well, if you're gonna
laugh at me, the hell with ya.

100
00:06:24,917 --> 00:06:27,511
The hell with you.

101
00:06:27,620 --> 00:06:30,020
I'll square myself with Lazarre,
if you don't mind.

102
00:06:30,089 --> 00:06:32,990
That's why God invented cards.

103
00:06:35,495 --> 00:06:38,328
- There is one thing
you can do for me.
- Name it.

104
00:06:38,398 --> 00:06:40,889
Think about what
protecting Bernie gets us.

105
00:06:40,967 --> 00:06:43,561
Think about what
offending Caspar loses us.

106
00:06:43,669 --> 00:06:46,035
Oh, come on, Tommy.
You know I don't like to think.

107
00:06:46,105 --> 00:06:48,164
Yeah.

108
00:06:48,241 --> 00:06:50,900
Well, think about
whether you should start.

109
00:08:36,148 --> 00:08:38,480
Wake up, Tommy.

110
00:08:38,551 --> 00:08:41,679
- I am awake.
- Your eyes are shut.

111
00:08:41,754 --> 00:08:44,018
Who you gonna believe?

112
00:08:46,826 --> 00:08:48,953
[ Groans ]

113
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:57,228
- How'd I do?
- What do you think?

114
00:08:57,303 --> 00:09:00,136
You are a millionaire.
You gonna remember your friends?

115
00:09:03,409 --> 00:09:07,072
- Where's me hat?
- You bet it, mug.

116
00:09:07,146 --> 00:09:10,673
Good thing the game broke up
before you bet your trousers.

117
00:09:11,918 --> 00:09:15,183
- [ Bangs Chair]
- Who made off with me hat?

118
00:09:15,254 --> 00:09:18,052
Verna. Verna and Mink.

119
00:09:18,124 --> 00:09:20,524
- Who?
- Mink and Verna.

120
00:09:22,395 --> 00:09:25,364
[ Vomiting ]

121
00:09:28,301 --> 00:09:30,667
Is Thunderclap running tonight?

122
00:09:30,736 --> 00:09:33,967
Thunderclap?
Yeah.

123
00:09:34,040 --> 00:09:36,065
What's she leaving at?

124
00:09:36,142 --> 00:09:38,804
Three to one, more than likely.

125
00:09:38,878 --> 00:09:42,109
Lay off, Tom. You shouldn't go
deeper in the hole.

126
00:09:42,181 --> 00:09:44,706
[ Groans ]
Tell Lazarre...

127
00:09:44,784 --> 00:09:48,242
I want 500 on the nose.

128
00:09:48,354 --> 00:09:50,879
You would have it.

129
00:10:03,803 --> 00:10:06,499
I want me hat.

130
00:10:06,606 --> 00:10:10,406
Is that all you came for?

131
00:10:10,476 --> 00:10:12,808
Yeah. I want me hat.

132
00:10:12,878 --> 00:10:15,039
It's mine. I won it.

133
00:10:15,114 --> 00:10:17,878
- What are you gonna do with it?
- Drop dead.

134
00:10:26,359 --> 00:10:29,260
I need a drink.

135
00:10:29,328 --> 00:10:31,956
Why didn't you say so?

136
00:10:54,120 --> 00:10:55,644
[ Knocking On Door ]

137
00:10:58,157 --> 00:11:00,717
[ Knocking Continues ]

138
00:11:08,734 --> 00:11:11,202
[ Knocking Continues ]

139
00:11:28,454 --> 00:11:31,548
Hello, Tommy.
Sorry about the hour.

140
00:11:31,624 --> 00:11:35,458
- I'll live. What's the rumpus?
- Can I come in?

141
00:11:38,030 --> 00:11:40,555
Sure.

142
00:11:49,241 --> 00:11:52,438
- Drink?
- I wouldn't mind.

143
00:11:59,285 --> 00:12:01,344
I tried callin' earlier.

144
00:12:01,454 --> 00:12:04,082
I got home late.

145
00:12:09,295 --> 00:12:14,665
- Well, uh, I'm sorry about the hour.
- Uh-huh.

146
00:12:27,046 --> 00:12:30,641
- Not bad.
- Better than the paint
we sell at the club.

147
00:12:30,716 --> 00:12:33,344
That it is. That it is.

148
00:12:36,922 --> 00:12:39,117
- You thought about
cutting Bernie loose?
- Can't do it, Tommy.

149
00:12:39,225 --> 00:12:42,194
Can't do it.

150
00:12:42,294 --> 00:12:44,819
That's sort of why I'm, uh--

151
00:12:47,433 --> 00:12:50,459
Tommy, I don't know where Verna is.

152
00:12:50,536 --> 00:12:53,835
- Uh-huh.
- I know what you're thinkin',
what else is new?

153
00:12:53,906 --> 00:12:56,898
But the situation now--
I'm worried.

154
00:12:57,009 --> 00:13:00,445
Verna can take care of herself,
maybe better than you can.

155
00:13:00,513 --> 00:13:04,040
- What does that mean?
- Want another one?

156
00:13:04,116 --> 00:13:06,050
No.

157
00:13:06,118 --> 00:13:08,177
What does that mean?

158
00:13:08,254 --> 00:13:10,654
How far she got
her hooks into you?

159
00:13:10,723 --> 00:13:12,816
That's a hell of a question.

160
00:13:14,994 --> 00:13:17,258
It's a grift.

161
00:13:17,329 --> 00:13:20,992
If she didn't need you
to protect her brother
from Johnny Caspar,

162
00:13:21,066 --> 00:13:24,729
you think she'd still be going
on slow carriage rides with you
through the park?

163
00:13:24,804 --> 00:13:29,207
That's the deal, isn't it?
You keep Bernie under wraps
till Caspar cools down?

164
00:13:29,275 --> 00:13:33,143
Jesus, you're a prickly pear.
What's wrong with her wanting
her brother taken care of?

165
00:13:33,212 --> 00:13:35,180
Nothing. I don't blame her.

166
00:13:35,247 --> 00:13:37,579
She sees the angle,
which is you, she plays it.

167
00:13:37,650 --> 00:13:40,619
She's a grifter,
just like her brother.

168
00:13:40,686 --> 00:13:42,950
Probably had grifter parents
and grifter grandparents...

169
00:13:43,022 --> 00:13:46,116
and someday they're each
gonna spawn little grifter kids.

170
00:13:46,192 --> 00:13:49,423
Stop it, Tommy.
I don't like to hear my friends
run down, even by other friends.

171
00:13:49,495 --> 00:13:51,690
- Friendship's got
nothing to do with it.
- The hell you say.

172
00:13:51,764 --> 00:13:54,528
You'd do anything to help
your friends, like you'd do
anything to kick your enemies.

173
00:13:54,633 --> 00:13:56,001
- Wrong, Leo.
You do things for a reason.
- Okay, Tom.

174
00:13:56,001 --> 00:13:57,935
- Wrong, Leo.
You do things for a reason.
- Okay, Tom.

175
00:13:58,003 --> 00:14:01,131
You know all the angles,
Christ, better than anybody.

176
00:14:03,108 --> 00:14:06,305
But maybe you're wrong
about this. You don't know
what's in Verna's heart.

177
00:14:06,378 --> 00:14:09,245
Leo, if she's such an angel,

178
00:14:09,315 --> 00:14:11,579
why are you looking for her
at 4:00 in the morning?

179
00:14:13,986 --> 00:14:15,954
[ Sighs ]

180
00:14:16,021 --> 00:14:17,955
I put a tail on her this afternoon.

181
00:14:19,391 --> 00:14:24,021
- Uh-huh.
- I asked Rug Daniels
to follow her around,

182
00:14:24,096 --> 00:14:27,293
just, you know,
to keep her out of trouble.

183
00:14:27,366 --> 00:14:31,496
I was worried.
After that meeting with Caspar,
you can't be too careful.

184
00:14:31,570 --> 00:14:34,903
- So what did Rug say that has you
scurrying over here?
- That's just it.

185
00:14:34,974 --> 00:14:40,640
- Nothing. He's disappeared.
- So you lost your lady friend
and the tail you put on her?

186
00:14:40,713 --> 00:14:43,307
I guess it does sound
pretty sorry at that.

187
00:14:43,382 --> 00:14:46,840
Help me out, Tom.
I wouldn't know where
to start lookin'.

188
00:14:46,919 --> 00:14:49,479
You know Rug's crowd.
You know the people Verna runs with.

189
00:14:49,555 --> 00:14:53,184
It's just I'm worried now
with things the way they are
between me and Caspar.

190
00:14:53,292 --> 00:14:56,125
You shouldn't be confronting
Johnny Caspar. That's what
I've been trying to tell you.

191
00:14:56,195 --> 00:14:59,028
You can't trade
body blows with him.
He's gotten too strong.

192
00:14:59,098 --> 00:15:03,057
I reckon I can still trade body blows
with any man in this town.

193
00:15:07,172 --> 00:15:09,902
Except you, Tom.

194
00:15:10,009 --> 00:15:11,943
And Verna.

195
00:15:16,982 --> 00:15:20,315
[ Chuckles ]

196
00:15:21,921 --> 00:15:24,515
Okay. Give me the needle.

197
00:15:26,392 --> 00:15:29,520
I am a sap.
[ Grunts ]

198
00:15:29,628 --> 00:15:32,961
I deserve it.

199
00:15:33,032 --> 00:15:35,125
Thanks for the drink.

200
00:15:36,568 --> 00:15:38,934
Let me know
if you hear anything.

201
00:16:07,499 --> 00:16:11,026
- Who was that?
- Leo.

202
00:16:11,136 --> 00:16:13,366
He's lookin' for you.

203
00:16:13,439 --> 00:16:15,907
Did you tell him I was here?

204
00:16:15,975 --> 00:16:18,466
No.

205
00:16:20,913 --> 00:16:24,314
Did you put in a good word
for my brother?

206
00:16:24,383 --> 00:16:26,476
No.

207
00:16:26,585 --> 00:16:29,816
- You said you would.
- I said I'd think about it.

208
00:16:31,924 --> 00:16:34,085
What did you tell him?

209
00:16:37,129 --> 00:16:39,962
Did you see
Rug Daniels last night?

210
00:16:40,032 --> 00:16:42,398
No.

211
00:16:42,468 --> 00:16:44,561
What did you tell Leo?

212
00:16:44,670 --> 00:16:47,298
I told him you were a tramp
and he should dump you.

213
00:16:51,276 --> 00:16:54,109
You're a son of a bitch, Tom.

214
00:16:57,616 --> 00:16:59,550
###[ Man Whistling ]

215
00:17:36,388 --> 00:17:38,549
[ Barking ]

216
00:17:43,929 --> 00:17:46,420
[ Chattering, Indistinct ]

217
00:18:00,345 --> 00:18:03,280
[ Car Horns Sounding ]

218
00:18:07,286 --> 00:18:09,413
- Hello, Tom.
What's the rumpus?
- Mink.

219
00:18:09,488 --> 00:18:11,581
- I see you got your hat back.
- Yeah, what of it?

220
00:18:11,657 --> 00:18:13,750
Not a thing. Look,
if it ain't my business,
I got not a thing to say.

221
00:18:13,826 --> 00:18:15,760
Listen, Bernie wants to see you.
It's important.

222
00:18:15,828 --> 00:18:17,762
Yeah, well, I'm right here.
I'm not made of glass.

223
00:18:17,830 --> 00:18:20,492
He's nervous walkin' around
in public. He's a right guy,
but he's very nervous.

224
00:18:20,599 --> 00:18:23,159
I mean, who wouldn't be?
In the spot he's in,
who wouldn't be?

225
00:18:23,268 --> 00:18:25,600
He asked me to ask you
to ask Leo to take care of him.

226
00:18:25,671 --> 00:18:27,696
Leo listens to you.
Not that Leo wouldn't help
a shmatte anyway.

227
00:18:27,773 --> 00:18:30,105
A guy like Bernie?
A straight shooter like him?

228
00:18:30,175 --> 00:18:32,973
- I don't get it, Mink.
- What's to get? It's as plain
as the nose on your face.

229
00:18:33,045 --> 00:18:35,377
- I thought you were
Eddie Dane's sycophant.
- Yeah, Tom, that's right,

230
00:18:35,447 --> 00:18:37,381
but a guy can have more
than one friend, can't he?

231
00:18:37,449 --> 00:18:40,577
Not that I want the Dane to know
about it, but the shmatte,
he's a right guy, Tommy.

232
00:18:40,686 --> 00:18:43,246
He's got a mixed reputation,
but for a sheeny, he's got
a lot of good qualities.

233
00:18:43,355 --> 00:18:46,620
- What's goin' on
between you and Bernie?
- Nothin', Tom.

234
00:18:46,692 --> 00:18:48,717
We're just...
friends, you know, amigos.

235
00:18:48,794 --> 00:18:51,160
You're a fickle boy, Mink.

236
00:18:51,230 --> 00:18:55,530
If Eddie Dane finds out
that you got another "amigo"- -

237
00:18:55,601 --> 00:18:59,230
- Well, I don't peg him
for the understanding type.
- Find out?

238
00:18:59,338 --> 00:19:01,932
How's he gonna find out?
Damn it, you and me
ain't even been talkin'!

239
00:19:02,007 --> 00:19:04,475
Jesus, Tom! Damn it! Jesus!

240
00:19:04,543 --> 00:19:06,704
[ Men Chuckling ]

241
00:19:06,778 --> 00:19:09,303
[ Leo ]
Hello, Tommy.

242
00:19:09,381 --> 00:19:12,578
- You know O'Doole and the mayor?
- I oughta.

243
00:19:12,651 --> 00:19:15,313
Voted for him six times last May.

244
00:19:15,387 --> 00:19:17,446
And that ain't the record, either.

245
00:19:17,556 --> 00:19:19,490
- [ Laughs ]
- [ Laughs ]

246
00:19:19,558 --> 00:19:23,688
Oh, Verna turned up.
She's downstairs.

247
00:19:23,762 --> 00:19:27,095
- She say where she'd been?
- No. I didn't want to press her.

248
00:19:27,166 --> 00:19:31,535
- You hear about Rug?
- Yeah. R.I.P.

249
00:19:31,603 --> 00:19:34,595
They took his hair, Tommy.

250
00:19:34,673 --> 00:19:37,369
Jesus, that's strange.
Why would they do that?

251
00:19:37,476 --> 00:19:41,970
- Maybe it was injuns.
- "Eye-ties," more like it.

252
00:19:44,149 --> 00:19:46,083
Giovanni Gasparo.

253
00:19:46,151 --> 00:19:49,018
So you figure Caspar bumped Rug.

254
00:19:49,087 --> 00:19:51,715
- Well, it's pretty obvious, ain't it?
- Yeah?

255
00:19:51,790 --> 00:19:56,784
- So what's the plan?
- Well, we'll jump on the guinea
hard with both feet.

256
00:19:56,895 --> 00:20:00,353
- Give him the lowdown, Dale.
- Yes. Well, um,

257
00:20:00,465 --> 00:20:03,195
Leo here just reminded us
that Mr. Caspar operates...

258
00:20:03,268 --> 00:20:05,293
several clubs in our city,

259
00:20:05,370 --> 00:20:09,363
wherein the patrons
imbibe of rum and play
at games of chance.

260
00:20:09,441 --> 00:20:11,602
And we're supposed to
stop the party.

261
00:20:11,677 --> 00:20:14,737
- They don't look
to happy about it, Leo.
- Oh, no, it ain't that, Tom.

262
00:20:14,846 --> 00:20:17,872
- Jesus, Tom, we do as we're told.
- Maybe they're right
not to like it.

263
00:20:17,983 --> 00:20:21,111
Stirring up this hornet's nest
won't be good for anyone,
and it'll mean killing.

264
00:20:21,186 --> 00:20:24,280
I'm not thrilled
about it either, but I can't
just lay down to Caspar.

265
00:20:24,356 --> 00:20:26,916
You could do worse.
You might not like it, but
giving up Bernie Bernbaum...

266
00:20:26,992 --> 00:20:28,960
is a pretty small price
to pay for peace.

267
00:20:29,027 --> 00:20:32,121
Business is business,
and a war is going to hurt everybody.

268
00:20:32,197 --> 00:20:34,563
Bernie plays with fire,
he's got to deal
with the consequences.

269
00:20:34,633 --> 00:20:36,601
Even if that means
he gets bumped off.

270
00:20:36,702 --> 00:20:40,695
SweetJesus, Tom, that ain't
even the point anymore.
Caspar pooped Rug.

271
00:20:40,772 --> 00:20:43,605
The day I back down
from a fight, Caspar's
welcome to the rackets,

272
00:20:43,675 --> 00:20:45,734
this town and my place
at the table.

273
00:20:45,811 --> 00:20:47,904
- I didn't start this thing, but--
- You did start it.

274
00:20:47,980 --> 00:20:51,472
- You and Verna.
- We can dangle, Leo,
if you'd prefer.

275
00:20:51,583 --> 00:20:53,574
Sit down, Dale!
We're all friends here.

276
00:20:53,685 --> 00:20:57,121
And Caspar hasn't
broken the rules, Bernie has,
and you, too, by helping him.

277
00:20:57,222 --> 00:20:59,383
And if that isn't enough,
consider that if you
make this a war,

278
00:20:59,458 --> 00:21:01,551
you have more to lose than Caspar.

279
00:21:01,627 --> 00:21:05,723
Okay, but more to beat him with.
Jesus, Tom, the two of us
have faced worse odds.

280
00:21:05,797 --> 00:21:14,439
Never without reason.
It helps to have one.

281
00:21:14,439 --> 00:21:17,374
[ Scoffs ]
Well, it's your call.

282
00:21:19,011 --> 00:21:21,309
My opinion used to count
for something around here.

283
00:21:21,380 --> 00:21:23,507
But it's always yours
to take or leave.

284
00:21:23,582 --> 00:21:25,550
Come on, Tommy.
It's not like that.

285
00:21:27,052 --> 00:21:30,044
Goddamn it!

286
00:21:32,391 --> 00:21:35,155
Goddamn kid's just like a twist.

287
00:21:35,227 --> 00:21:37,718
Get me a stiff one.

288
00:21:39,131 --> 00:21:41,429
No small talk, huh?

289
00:21:43,669 --> 00:21:46,968
- They shoot your horse?
- If there's any justice.

290
00:21:48,407 --> 00:21:50,898
- Verna around?
- She stepped into
the ladies' room.

291
00:21:50,976 --> 00:21:54,241
- You got Lazarre's 500?
- You'll have to carry me
for a few days.

292
00:21:54,313 --> 00:21:57,373
He ain't gonna like that.
Couldn't you get it from Leo?

293
00:21:57,449 --> 00:22:00,748
It's not Leo's debt.
I'll pay me own way.

294
00:22:00,819 --> 00:22:02,650
I admire a man of principle.

295
00:22:04,456 --> 00:22:07,425
Does this go on the tab?

296
00:22:07,492 --> 00:22:10,188
- [ Women Gasping ]
- Close your eyes, ladies.
I'm coming through.

297
00:22:14,533 --> 00:22:18,060
- Who's the war paint for?
- Go home and dry out.

298
00:22:19,237 --> 00:22:21,262
You don't need it for Leo,
believe me.

299
00:22:21,340 --> 00:22:23,831
He already thinks you're
the original Miss Jesus.

300
00:22:23,909 --> 00:22:26,002
- What the hell's
the matter with you?
- What's the matter with you?

301
00:22:26,111 --> 00:22:29,672
- Afraid people might get
the right idea?
- Leo's got the right idea.

302
00:22:29,748 --> 00:22:32,410
I like him.
He's honest and he's got a heart.

303
00:22:32,484 --> 00:22:34,748
Then it's true what they say--
opposites attract.

304
00:22:34,820 --> 00:22:38,312
- Do me a favor.
Mind your own business.
- This is my business.

305
00:22:38,390 --> 00:22:41,257
Intimidating helpless women
is part of what I do.

306
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:43,487
- Then find one
and intimidate her.
- Leo's upstairs...

307
00:22:43,595 --> 00:22:45,961
getting ready to shoot himself
in the foot on your account.

308
00:22:46,031 --> 00:22:47,965
- I don't know
what you're talkin'about.
- He's gonna go to the mat...

309
00:22:48,033 --> 00:22:49,967
for your brother,
and it's gonna hurt him.

310
00:22:50,035 --> 00:22:52,230
I don't know Leo's business,
but he's a big boy.

311
00:22:52,304 --> 00:22:54,329
- He used to be.
- Look, what do you want, Tom?

312
00:22:54,406 --> 00:22:57,239
You want me to pretend
I don't care what happens to Bernie?

313
00:22:57,309 --> 00:23:00,039
Well, I do.
He's my brother. I don't
want to see him get hurt.

314
00:23:00,145 --> 00:23:04,514
If Leo wants to help out,
I'll step out with him,
show him a good time in return.

315
00:23:04,583 --> 00:23:07,950
- There's no harm in that.
- There's a name for that kind
of business arrangement.

316
00:23:08,019 --> 00:23:11,546
Look, I'll do what I have to do
to protect Bernie.

317
00:23:11,623 --> 00:23:13,955
There's no reason for you
to try and queer that.

318
00:23:14,025 --> 00:23:16,653
Regardless of what
you think about me,
Bernie's a decent guy.

319
00:23:16,728 --> 00:23:20,391
- A straight shooter, huh?
A square "G."
- Yeah.

320
00:23:20,499 --> 00:23:24,765
Sneer at him like everyone else,
just because he's different.

321
00:23:24,836 --> 00:23:27,498
People think he's a degenerate.
People think he's scum.

322
00:23:27,572 --> 00:23:31,167
- Well, he's not.
- Poor misunderstood Bernie.

323
00:23:31,243 --> 00:23:33,677
What is this about, Tom?

324
00:23:33,745 --> 00:23:37,181
You want me to stop seeing Leo?
Why don't you just say so?

325
00:23:39,050 --> 00:23:42,486
I want you to quit
spinning Leo in circles
and pointing him where to go.

326
00:23:42,554 --> 00:23:45,022
- I forgot. That's your job.
- I'll do what I have to do
to protect Leo.

327
00:23:45,090 --> 00:23:48,491
I'm asking you politely.
Leave him alone.
I don't have to ask.

328
00:23:48,560 --> 00:23:51,757
If I told him about our little
dance last night, your pool
would pretty soon dry up.

329
00:23:51,830 --> 00:23:53,889
So would yours.
I don't like being threatened.

330
00:23:53,965 --> 00:23:58,163
I don't like being taken for
a sucker. That might work with
Leo, but it don't work with me.

331
00:23:58,270 --> 00:24:01,398
Do you think last night
was just more campaigning
for my brother?

332
00:24:01,473 --> 00:24:03,373
I can see the angles.

333
00:24:03,442 --> 00:24:05,535
You know, if there was a market
for little old ladies,

334
00:24:05,610 --> 00:24:07,601
you'd have Grandma Bernbaum
first in line.

335
00:24:07,679 --> 00:24:10,409
- You're a pathetic rumhead.
- And I love you, angel.

336
00:24:26,932 --> 00:24:29,958
I suppose you think
you raised hell.

337
00:24:34,005 --> 00:24:37,600
Sister, when I've raised hell,
you'll know it.

338
00:24:40,545 --> 00:24:43,480
[ Phone Ringing ]

339
00:24:43,548 --> 00:24:45,812
[ Door Opening ]

340
00:25:14,412 --> 00:25:17,848
- Yeah.
- [ Man ] Lazarre wants
his money. He wants it now.

341
00:25:17,916 --> 00:25:20,407
- I need a couple of days.
- Yeah? How come is that?

342
00:25:20,485 --> 00:25:24,717
- Because I don't have it.
- All right, welsher, how do I
know you ain't got it?

343
00:25:24,789 --> 00:25:28,850
- Because I say so.
- That ain't gonna be good enough.

344
00:25:28,927 --> 00:25:32,522
- What would be good enough?
- Lazarre ain't gonna
like it one bit.

345
00:25:32,631 --> 00:25:35,566
Tell Lazarre if he's not happy,
he can send someone over
to break my legs.

346
00:25:35,634 --> 00:25:38,626
I won't squawk.

347
00:25:40,272 --> 00:25:42,968
- Hello, Bernie.
- Hello, Tom.

348
00:25:43,041 --> 00:25:46,670
- What's the rumpus?
- Come on in.
Make yourself at home.

349
00:25:46,745 --> 00:25:49,305
Yeah, you weren't here,
so I thought I'd do that.

350
00:25:49,381 --> 00:25:51,679
I didn't want to answer
the phone, though. I figured...

351
00:25:51,783 --> 00:25:53,717
it wasn't for me.

352
00:25:55,520 --> 00:25:58,318
[ Chuckles ]
I get it. Get to the point, huh?

353
00:25:58,390 --> 00:26:01,154
Okay. The point is,
I'm a good guy.

354
00:26:01,226 --> 00:26:03,160
I've heard that
from a lot of people today.

355
00:26:03,228 --> 00:26:05,128
Good guy, lots of friends.
That's the way it works.

356
00:26:05,196 --> 00:26:09,860
Maybe if you appreciated me
a little more, you wouldn't
be making waves with Leo.

357
00:26:09,968 --> 00:26:12,766
It's a bad time to be
doing that. Right now,
we're both in a jam.

358
00:26:12,837 --> 00:26:16,500
I hear you're on a bad streak.
Short of funds.

359
00:26:16,575 --> 00:26:19,874
Well, I got that crazy dago
mad at me.

360
00:26:19,945 --> 00:26:21,913
Don't ask me why.
I'm just a small-timer...

361
00:26:21,980 --> 00:26:24,278
trying to get by
like everyone else.

362
00:26:24,349 --> 00:26:27,341
I need help from my friends
like Leo and you.

363
00:26:27,419 --> 00:26:29,512
Leo gets your sister.
What are you sellin' me?

364
00:26:29,621 --> 00:26:32,021
Come on, Tom.
It's not like that at all.
It wasn't my idea.

365
00:26:32,090 --> 00:26:34,183
She'll sleep with anyone.
You know that.

366
00:26:34,259 --> 00:26:37,922
She even tried to teach me
a thing or two about bed artistry.

367
00:26:37,996 --> 00:26:40,829
Can you believe that?
[ Chuckles ]

368
00:26:40,899 --> 00:26:43,163
My own sister.
[ Chuckles ]

369
00:26:43,234 --> 00:26:48,365
Some crackpot idea about
saving me from my friends.

370
00:26:48,473 --> 00:26:50,600
She's a sick twist, all right.

371
00:26:50,709 --> 00:26:54,509
- She speaks highly of you.
- Yeah, well, you stick
by your family.

372
00:26:54,579 --> 00:26:57,139
The point is, I can help you
with your debts if that
would make us friends.

373
00:26:57,215 --> 00:27:00,616
My motto is,
"A guy can't have too many."

374
00:27:00,685 --> 00:27:03,848
Big payday Saturday, Tom.
You could be in on it.

375
00:27:03,922 --> 00:27:06,220
Another fix? Which fight?

376
00:27:06,324 --> 00:27:10,351
That's confidential
at the moment. But it
doesn't have to stay that way.

377
00:27:10,462 --> 00:27:12,760
How come you know
so much about it?

378
00:27:12,831 --> 00:27:14,958
Caspar isn't laying
any more bets with you.

379
00:27:20,005 --> 00:27:22,872
You really must have Mink
jumping through hoops.

380
00:27:22,941 --> 00:27:26,274
Like I say, you can't
have too many.

381
00:27:26,378 --> 00:27:28,812
[ Exhales Deeply ]

382
00:27:30,615 --> 00:27:34,608
- We got a deal?
- I'll think about it.

383
00:27:37,088 --> 00:27:39,420
I wouldn't want it any other way.

384
00:27:42,360 --> 00:27:44,920
Hey, Adolph.

385
00:27:46,898 --> 00:27:49,867
- My credit still
good with you?
- Mmm.

386
00:27:49,934 --> 00:27:52,630
Give me a hundred across on Tailor Made
in the third tonight.

387
00:27:52,704 --> 00:27:56,037
- Lazarre won't like it.
- Try 50 across.

388
00:27:56,107 --> 00:27:58,541
I'll try.
It's another 150 you'll owe him.

389
00:27:58,610 --> 00:28:02,011
- Only if I lose, Adolph.
- Tommy, the way you're goin'--

390
00:28:02,080 --> 00:28:05,641
- Hey, horses got knees?
- I don't know. Fetlocks.

391
00:28:05,750 --> 00:28:09,709
Well, if I was a horse,
I'd be down on my fetlocks
praying you don't bet on me.

392
00:28:09,788 --> 00:28:12,154
- Drift, small guy.
- Drop dead, ape.

393
00:28:12,223 --> 00:28:14,521
Come on, Tom.
Boss wants to see ya.

394
00:28:14,592 --> 00:28:16,992
He didn't have time
to engrave nothin' formal.

395
00:28:18,096 --> 00:28:21,657
[ Chattering In Italian ]

396
00:28:36,748 --> 00:28:41,208
What you mean, he's eatin' too much?
What's the goddamn doctor know?

397
00:28:42,320 --> 00:28:45,084
- What you eat for lunch?
- A hot dog.

398
00:28:45,156 --> 00:28:48,819
- Just a hot dog?
- A hot dog and mustard.

399
00:28:48,893 --> 00:28:53,455
A hot dog and mustard.
[ Laughs ]

400
00:28:53,565 --> 00:28:56,796
A hot dog and mustard!

401
00:28:58,503 --> 00:29:02,496
You hear that, Dane?
My kid is as smart as a whip.

402
00:29:02,574 --> 00:29:05,338
Even Uncle Eddie
thinks that's funny.

403
00:29:05,410 --> 00:29:08,311
Okay.

404
00:29:09,481 --> 00:29:13,008
Go ahead. Which hand
is the penny in?

405
00:29:14,319 --> 00:29:16,879
Choose again.

406
00:29:20,925 --> 00:29:24,122
Okay. Here you go.
Take the penny.
Shiny new penny.

407
00:29:24,195 --> 00:29:27,961
Take the kid,
wait in the car.
Give him a penny, boys!

408
00:29:29,868 --> 00:29:33,804
- I ain't got a penny, boss.
- That's a penny you owe him.

409
00:29:33,872 --> 00:29:37,399
Hello, Tom. What's the rumpus?
You like kids?

410
00:29:37,475 --> 00:29:40,740
- No.
- Have a seat. Go ahead.

411
00:29:42,247 --> 00:29:44,181
Well, you're missin' out
on a complete life.

412
00:29:44,249 --> 00:29:46,740
I know, kids, big deal.

413
00:29:46,818 --> 00:29:49,753
Still, I'm telling you.

414
00:29:49,821 --> 00:29:53,382
Anyways, thanks for comin' by.

415
00:29:54,926 --> 00:29:57,520
I just wrote this check out
to your bookmaker Lazarre.

416
00:29:57,595 --> 00:30:00,393
It's for an even 1,500,
which is more than I hear
you owe him,

417
00:30:00,465 --> 00:30:03,798
but I figured you could always
use some money on the cuff,
a high roller such as yourself.

418
00:30:03,868 --> 00:30:06,962
- What do you say?
- Thanks.

419
00:30:09,040 --> 00:30:11,440
Always the yapper, huh?
[ Chuckles ]

420
00:30:11,509 --> 00:30:15,878
Well, you're welcome.
You wanna know why I'm puttin'
you square with Lazarre?

421
00:30:15,947 --> 00:30:19,280
- Not particularly.
- I want everybody to be friends.

422
00:30:19,350 --> 00:30:21,716
I do this, you're friends
with Lazarre,

423
00:30:21,786 --> 00:30:24,448
he's friends with you,
you're friends with me.

424
00:30:24,522 --> 00:30:28,982
All you gotta do
to show you're a friend
is give me Bernie Bernbaum.

425
00:30:29,060 --> 00:30:32,496
You know it's
the right thing anyway.
The shmatte steals from me.

426
00:30:32,564 --> 00:30:36,591
I can't have Leo giving him
a shiny new penny.

427
00:30:36,668 --> 00:30:38,829
So the deal is,
I give you Bernie,

428
00:30:38,903 --> 00:30:41,428
smooth it over with Leo
and you bail me out with Lazarre.

429
00:30:41,506 --> 00:30:43,633
Yeah. Then we're all
friends again.
[ Chuckles ]

430
00:30:43,708 --> 00:30:46,438
You, me, Leo, the Dane.

431
00:30:46,511 --> 00:30:50,140
- We can maybe
have tea sometime.
- [ Caspar ] Come on, Eddie.

432
00:30:50,248 --> 00:30:53,217
Friends is a mental state.

433
00:30:53,284 --> 00:30:56,981
- What do you say, kid?
- I'll think about it.

434
00:30:57,055 --> 00:30:59,717
You'll think about it.
[ Chuckles ]

435
00:30:59,791 --> 00:31:02,726
You hear that, Dane?
The kid's a thinker.
That's terrific.

436
00:31:02,794 --> 00:31:06,662
- Does he want
a pillow for his head?
- Okay, kid. Think about it.

437
00:31:06,764 --> 00:31:10,564
It's a mental state.
If it'll help you think,

438
00:31:10,635 --> 00:31:13,195
you should know that if
you don't do this thing,

439
00:31:13,271 --> 00:31:15,831
you're not gonna be
in any shape to walk out of here.

440
00:31:17,642 --> 00:31:21,203
Would that be physically,
or just a mental state?

441
00:31:28,219 --> 00:31:31,586
That ain't friendly, kid.
I make you a nice offer,

442
00:31:31,656 --> 00:31:34,181
you give me the high hat.

443
00:32:14,198 --> 00:32:17,292
Hold it.

444
00:32:29,881 --> 00:32:33,112
Jesus, Tom.

445
00:33:13,725 --> 00:33:15,886
Just in the nick of time, huh?

446
00:33:19,831 --> 00:33:23,665
Well, no harm done.
Unless your friend broke his foot.

447
00:33:23,735 --> 00:33:27,102
- Where am I?
- Where are you? Johnny
Caspar's pleasure dome.

448
00:33:27,171 --> 00:33:30,106
Same as when you left us
about ten seconds ago.

449
00:33:30,174 --> 00:33:32,540
Hello, Tom. How are ya?

450
00:33:32,610 --> 00:33:34,805
Care to scrape a knuckle
on your playmate here?

451
00:33:34,879 --> 00:33:37,677
- No. Thanks though, Andy.
- Well, if you
change your mind,

452
00:33:37,749 --> 00:33:41,116
we'll be interrogating
for a while.

453
00:33:41,185 --> 00:33:44,552
- What was that party
about, anyway?
- We do this every weekend.

454
00:33:44,622 --> 00:33:47,216
Jesus, what is the matter
with you people?

455
00:33:47,291 --> 00:33:50,089
Well, they said make it hurt,
so we make it hurt.

456
00:33:56,467 --> 00:33:58,435
Drink, O'Doole?

457
00:33:58,503 --> 00:34:00,733
I'm on duty.

458
00:34:00,805 --> 00:34:03,535
To Volstead.

459
00:34:04,976 --> 00:34:07,103
- [ Bottle Breaks ]
- Any news about Rug?

460
00:34:07,178 --> 00:34:09,669
Still dead, far as I know.

461
00:34:09,747 --> 00:34:12,477
- Get a slug out of him?
- Yeah, .22.

462
00:34:12,550 --> 00:34:15,280
Listen, Tom, I'm just
the chief around here,

463
00:34:15,353 --> 00:34:17,412
so don't bother tellin' me
if you don't happen to
feel like it,

464
00:34:17,522 --> 00:34:19,456
but what the hell is Leo doin'?

465
00:34:19,524 --> 00:34:23,984
Make him listen to you, Tom.
It ain't right, all this fuss
over one sheeny.

466
00:34:24,062 --> 00:34:26,997
Let Caspar have Bernie.
What's one Hebrew more or less?

467
00:34:27,065 --> 00:34:28,999
We're burnin'
our meal ticket here.

468
00:34:29,067 --> 00:34:31,297
Leo will do what suits him,
and you'll do what he tells you.

469
00:34:31,369 --> 00:34:33,303
Last I heard, Leo was still
running this town.

470
00:34:33,371 --> 00:34:35,999
Yeah, well, he won't be
for long if this keeps up.

471
00:34:36,107 --> 00:34:38,871
It's no good for anyone.
You said as much yourself.

472
00:34:38,943 --> 00:34:43,141
First off, O'Doole, I can
say what I please to Leo
and about him.

473
00:34:43,214 --> 00:34:45,205
You can't.

474
00:34:45,283 --> 00:34:48,878
Second, once Leo decides,
that's that.

475
00:34:48,953 --> 00:34:51,387
If that sticks going down,
there are plenty
of coppers I know...

476
00:34:51,456 --> 00:34:54,323
who wouldn't mind
bein' chief and could
swallow it clean.

477
00:34:54,425 --> 00:34:58,486
Jesus, Tom,
I was just speculatin'
about a hypothesis.

478
00:34:58,596 --> 00:35:00,655
I know I don't
know nothin'.

479
00:35:00,731 --> 00:35:03,029
It's just a--
just a damn mess, is all.

480
00:35:03,101 --> 00:35:05,035
[ Machine Gun Fire ]

481
00:35:05,103 --> 00:35:08,334
[ Shouting, Indistinct ]

482
00:35:20,785 --> 00:35:22,252
[ Door Closes ]

483
00:35:22,320 --> 00:35:27,125
[ Dialing Phone ]

484
00:35:27,125 --> 00:35:29,093
Hello, Officer. I'd like to
report an intruder...

485
00:35:29,160 --> 00:35:32,186
at 346 West Lewis--

486
00:35:32,296 --> 00:35:35,891
Who's this?
Hello, Shad. Tom Reagan here.

487
00:35:35,967 --> 00:35:38,765
- You need the booze?
- [ Tom ] No, we won't be
needing any today.

488
00:35:38,836 --> 00:35:41,634
- False alarm, huh?
- Yeah. My mother.
She didn't recognize me.

489
00:35:41,706 --> 00:35:44,038
Let me talk to Mulveany.
Miss me?

490
00:35:44,108 --> 00:35:46,576
Drop dead.

491
00:35:46,677 --> 00:35:48,702
- Mulveany here.
- Sean?

492
00:35:48,813 --> 00:35:50,747
Tell O'Doole to get a car
over to Leo's tonight.

493
00:35:50,815 --> 00:35:53,784
If we're banging away
at Caspar, we oughta be ready
for him to bang back.

494
00:35:53,851 --> 00:35:56,115
- [ Hangs Up Phone ]
- What do you want?

495
00:35:56,187 --> 00:35:59,953
I was in the neighborhood,
feeling a bit daffy,

496
00:36:00,024 --> 00:36:02,925
so I thought I'd drop in
for an aperitif.

497
00:36:04,662 --> 00:36:07,631
- Rug Daniels is dead.
- Gee, that's tough.

498
00:36:07,698 --> 00:36:09,893
Don't get hysterical.

499
00:36:09,967 --> 00:36:13,562
I've had enough excitement
for one night without a dame
going all weepy on me.

500
00:36:13,638 --> 00:36:15,765
- I barely knew the gentleman.
- Rug?

501
00:36:15,840 --> 00:36:20,209
A bit of a shakedown artist,
not above the occasional grift.

502
00:36:20,278 --> 00:36:24,078
Bet you'd understand that.
All in all, not a bad guy,

503
00:36:24,148 --> 00:36:27,584
if looks, brains
and personality don't count.

504
00:36:27,652 --> 00:36:30,348
- You better hope they don't.
- Yeah, well- -

505
00:36:30,421 --> 00:36:33,015
We're none of us the saint
I hear your brother is.

506
00:36:33,090 --> 00:36:35,285
- Who killed him?
- Leo thinks Caspar did.

507
00:36:35,359 --> 00:36:37,327
- But you know better.
- I do now.

508
00:36:37,395 --> 00:36:40,660
You see, Caspar just tried
to buy me into fixing
his tiff with Leo,

509
00:36:40,731 --> 00:36:43,495
which he'd hardly do
if he was waging war.

510
00:36:43,568 --> 00:36:47,629
So I figure you killed him, angel.
You or St. Bernard.

511
00:36:47,738 --> 00:36:51,538
Why would I or my brother
kill Rug Daniels or anybody else?

512
00:36:51,609 --> 00:36:55,670
Rug was following you.
He knew about you and me,

513
00:36:55,746 --> 00:36:58,374
and that wouldn't help
your play with Leo, would it?

514
00:36:58,449 --> 00:37:00,542
You think I murdered someone?

515
00:37:00,618 --> 00:37:03,644
Come on, Tom.
You know me a little.

516
00:37:03,754 --> 00:37:06,245
Nobody knows anybody.
Not that well.

517
00:37:06,357 --> 00:37:08,552
You know, or you
wouldn't be here.

518
00:37:08,626 --> 00:37:11,993
Not at all, sugar.
I came to hear your side of the story.

519
00:37:12,063 --> 00:37:16,693
How horrible Rug was,
how he goaded you into it,
how he tried to shake you down.

520
00:37:16,767 --> 00:37:18,860
- That's not why
you came either.
- Tell me why I came.

521
00:37:18,936 --> 00:37:22,064
- The oldest reason there is.
- There are friendlier
places to drink.

522
00:37:22,173 --> 00:37:24,107
- Why can't you admit it?
- Admit what?

523
00:37:24,175 --> 00:37:27,508
That you don't like
me seeing Leo
'cause you're jealous.

524
00:37:27,578 --> 00:37:29,876
Admit that you've
got a heart,

525
00:37:29,947 --> 00:37:32,415
even though it may be
small and feeble...

526
00:37:32,483 --> 00:37:34,678
and you can't remember
the last time you used it.

527
00:37:34,752 --> 00:37:37,915
If I'd known we were gonna
cast our feelings into words,

528
00:37:37,989 --> 00:37:40,617
I'd have memorized
the Song of Solomon.

529
00:37:42,660 --> 00:37:45,891
Maybe that's why
I like you, Tom.

530
00:37:45,963 --> 00:37:48,761
I never knew anybody
that made being
a son of a bitch...

531
00:37:48,833 --> 00:37:51,529
such a point of pride.

532
00:37:51,602 --> 00:37:54,594
Though one day you'll
pay the price for it.

533
00:37:55,940 --> 00:37:59,808
Okay, Verna.
But until then, let's get stinko.

534
00:37:59,910 --> 00:38:02,378
Let's do something else first.

535
00:38:07,118 --> 00:38:09,518
[ Tom ]
Yeah. Let's do plenty.

